content: Yes, the principles established by the Treaty of Westphalia are still relevant today and continue to influence contemporary international relations. The concept of state sovereignty, territorial integrity, and non-interference has become a fundamental principle of modern international law and is incorporated into the United Nations Charter. The idea of the balance of power also remains a crucial aspect of international relations and has been played out in various global conflicts and power struggles. Overall, the Treaty of Westphalia remains a crucial turning point in European history and continues to shape the way the world operates today.
